---
import Layout from "@/components/Layout.astro";
import { withBase } from "@/lib/paths";
---

<Layout
  title="Who's who"
  description="A hand-curated guide to the Australian Government bodies with carriage of AI policy — who owns what, how they emerged, and where the transparency statements this site tracks fit in."
>
  <div class="page whoswho prose stack">
    <h1>Who&rsquo;s who</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      No one desk runs Australian Government AI policy. The rules for AI in the
      economy sit in one department, and the rules for the government&rsquo;s own use
      of AI in another. The delivery machinery sits in a third, and since July 2026 a
      new office in the Prime Minister&rsquo;s own department sits across the lot.
      This page is a guide to who holds which piece, how the cast has grown, and
      where the transparency statements this site tracks fit in.
    </p>
    <p>
      Unlike the rest of this site, which is generated from the daily scrape, this
      page is written and updated by hand. Every claim links to a government source,
      or to news coverage for announcements. Last reviewed 15 July 2026.
    </p>

    <h2 id="tracks">Two tracks, one new office</h2>
    <p>
      Most of the apparent sprawl resolves into two tracks. One sets policy for AI
      in the <em>economy</em>: what the businesses building and deploying AI should
      do. That work lives in the Department of Industry, Science and Resources. It
      runs from the <a href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/australias-ai-ethics-principles"
        >AI Ethics Principles</a
      > of 2019, through the safe-and-responsible-AI consultations of 2023&ndash;24,
      to the <a href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/national-ai-plan"
        >National AI Plan</a
      > of December 2025.
    </p>
    <p>
      The other track governs the <em>government&rsquo;s own</em> use of AI: what the
      public service may do with these tools, and what it must tell the public.
      Three bodies in the Finance portfolio share this work, all answering to the
      Minister for Finance and the Public Service, Senator Katy Gallagher. The
      Digital Transformation Agency writes the rules, the Department of Finance
      builds the shared tools, and the Australian Public Service Commission looks
      after the workforce. The transparency statements this site tracks belong to
      this second track: they are required by a DTA policy.
    </p>
    <p>
      The <a href="#office-of-ai">Office of AI</a> announced on 15 July 2026 is a bid
      to coordinate both tracks from the Department of the Prime Minister and
      Cabinet. Its ambit also takes in the data-centre, copyright, education and
      national-security threads around them.
    </p>

    <h2 id="cast">The cast</h2>

    <h3 id="dta">Digital Transformation Agency (DTA)</h3>
    <p>
      The DTA writes the rules for AI inside government, and it is the reason every
      statement on this site exists. An executive agency in the <a
        href="https://www.directory.gov.au/portfolios/finance/digital-transformation-agency"
        >Finance portfolio</a
      >, it descends from the Digital Transformation Office of 2015, renamed in
      2016. With the industry department it published the first whole-of-government <a
        href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/interim-guidance-generative-ai-government-agencies"
        >interim guidance on generative AI</a
      > in July 2023, and it jointly led the <a
        href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/ai-government-taskforce-examining-use-and-governance-ai-aps"
        >AI in Government Taskforce</a
      > (eighteen secondees from eleven agencies) from September 2023 to June 2024.
      It also ran the <a href="https://www.digital.gov.au/initiatives/copilot-trial"
        >whole-of-government Microsoft 365 Copilot trial</a
      > over the first half of 2024, across more than 60 agencies and around 7,600
      staff.
    </p>
    <p>
      Its central instrument is the <a
        href="https://www.digital.gov.au/ai/ai-in-government-policy"
        ><em>Policy for the responsible use of AI in government</em></a
      >, <a
        href="https://ministers.finance.gov.au/financeminister/media-release/2024/08/15/new-policy-use-ai-government"
        >announced in August 2024</a
      > and effective that September, with a substantially <a
        href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/ai-policy-update-strengthening-responsible-use-across-government"
        >strengthened v2.0</a
      > from 15 December 2025. Under it sits the <a
        href="https://www.digital.gov.au/ai/ai-in-government-policy/standard-ai-transparency-statements"
        >Standard for AI transparency statements</a
      >, which required agencies to publish a statement by 28 February 2025. Those
      statements are the documents whose every change this site records. The DTA
      also publishes a <a
        href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/new-ai-technical-standard-support-responsible-government-adoption"
        >technical standard for government AI systems</a
      > (July 2025) and an AI impact assessment tool with procurement guidance
      (December 2025); since <a
        href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/new-central-register-ai-transparency-statements-commonwealth-entities"
        >March 2026</a
      > it keeps a central register of the transparency statements themselves. An AI
      Review Committee to oversee high-risk use cases across government was slated
      to be detailed by mid-2026. The CEO is <a href="https://www.dta.gov.au/chris-fechner-ceo"
        >Chris Fechner</a
      >.
    </p>

    <h3 id="finance">Department of Finance: AIDE and GovAI</h3>
    <p>
      Finance is the delivery arm. It led the <a
        href="https://www.digital.gov.au/policy/ai/australian-public-service-ai-plan-2025"
        ><em>AI Plan for the Australian Public Service</em></a
      >, <a
        href="https://ministers.finance.gov.au/financeminister/speech/2025/11/12/launch-ai-plan-australian-public-service"
        >launched by Senator Katy Gallagher on 12 November 2025</a
      > around three pillars: trust, people, tools. Its coordination function is <a
        href="https://www.govai.gov.au/aide">AI Delivery and Enablement (AIDE)</a
      >, a central multidisciplinary team <a
        href="https://www.finance.gov.au/about-us/news/2025/aide-and-govai-moving-experimentation-impact-across-aps"
        >stood up in late 2025</a
      >. AIDE leads delivery of the plan and runs the shared platforms; it also
      reports on AI adoption across the service. Finance operates <a
        href="https://www.govai.gov.au/about">GovAI</a
      >, the APS-only AI platform, piloted from 2024 and <a
        href="https://ministers.finance.gov.au/financeminister/media-release/2025/07/31/govai-launch-marks-major-milestone-ai-aps"
        >opened to the whole service on 31 July 2025</a
      >. GovAI&rsquo;s generative assistant, GovAI Chat, entered an <a
        href="https://www.finance.gov.au/about-us/news/2026/govai-chat-alpha-trial-now-open-sign-now"
        >alpha trial in April 2026</a
      >, offering commercial models such as ChatGPT and Claude inside a
      government-managed environment.
    </p>
    <p>
      The plan also required every non-corporate agency to appoint an SES-level <a
        href="https://www.finance.gov.au/about-us/news/2025/establishing-chief-ai-officers-aps"
        >Chief AI Officer</a
      > by July 2026. AIDE convenes these officers, whose role is distinct from the
      accountable officials the DTA&rsquo;s policy already required. By the
      deadline, <a
        href="https://ia.acs.org.au/article/2026/govt-agencies-that-missed-the-chief-ai-officer-deadline.html"
        >104 of the 106 agencies obliged to appoint one had done so</a
      >.
    </p>

    <h3 id="apsc">Australian Public Service Commission (APSC)</h3>
    <p>
      The APSC owns the workforce piece. Under the APS AI Plan&rsquo;s <a
        href="https://www.digital.gov.au/policy/ai/australian-public-service-ai-plan-2025/people"
        >people pillar</a
      > it leads foundational AI training, delivered through the APS Academy and <a
        href="https://ia.acs.org.au/article/2026/govt-agencies-that-missed-the-chief-ai-officer-deadline.html"
        >completed by more than 100,000 public servants by July 2026</a
      >. It also sets the standards for consulting staff on AI-related workplace
      change and hosts an <a
        href="https://www.apsc.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/aps-professional-streams/aps-human-resources-hr-profession/aps-hr-professional-news/harnessing-benefits-ai-while-supporting-our-changing-workforce"
        >AI Workforce Planning Taskforce</a
      >; in April 2026 it published <a
        href="https://www.apsc.gov.au/working-aps/hr-practitioners/recruitment-aps/ai-recruitment"
        >principles for AI in recruitment</a
      >. Despite a common assumption, the 2023&ndash;24 AI in Government Taskforce
      was jointly led by the DTA and the industry department,
      <a
        href="https://www.apsc.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/workforce-information/research-analysis-and-publications/state-service/state-service-report-2023-24/fit-future/supporting-safe-and-responsible-use-artificial-intelligence"
        >not by the APSC</a
      >.
    </p>

    <h3 id="disr">Department of Industry, Science and Resources (DISR)</h3>
    <p>
      DISR sets AI policy for the economy at large, and it has housed the long
      debate over whether Australia should regulate AI directly. It published the <a
        href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/australias-ai-ethics-principles"
        >AI Ethics Principles</a
      > in 2019, developed with CSIRO&rsquo;s Data61, and the <a
        href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/australias-artificial-intelligence-action-plan"
        >AI Action Plan</a
      > in 2021. Under Minister Ed Husic it ran the <a
        href="https://consult.industry.gov.au/supporting-responsible-ai"
        >safe and responsible AI consultation</a
      > of 2023, which drew more than 500 submissions. A January 2024 <a
        href="https://www.industry.gov.au/news/australian-governments-interim-response-safe-and-responsible-ai-consultation"
        >interim response</a
      > promised guardrails for high-risk AI; an <a
        href="https://www.minister.industry.gov.au/ministers/husic/media-releases/new-artificial-intelligence-expert-group"
        >AI Expert Group</a
      > followed, then a <a href="https://consult.industry.gov.au/ai-mandatory-guardrails"
        >mandatory-guardrails proposals paper</a
      > in September 2024.
    </p>
    <p>
      The direction changed with the ministry. Husic was dropped in the May 2025
      reshuffle; <a href="https://www.minister.industry.gov.au/ministers/timayres"
        >Senator Tim Ayres</a
      > became Minister for Industry and Innovation and Minister for Science, with <a
        href="https://www.minister.industry.gov.au/charlton">Dr Andrew Charlton</a
      > as Assistant Minister for Science, Technology and the Digital Economy. Their
      <a
        href="https://www.industry.gov.au/news/australia-launches-national-ai-plan-capture-opportunities-share-benefits-and-keep-australians-safe"
        >National AI Plan</a
      > of 2 December 2025 chose existing legal and regulatory frameworks over a
      dedicated AI Act, and the mandatory-guardrails proposal did not proceed. DISR
      also carries Australia&rsquo;s international AI-safety commitments, from the <a
        href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/bletchley-declaration-countries-attending-ai-safety-summit-1-2-november-2023"
        >Bletchley Declaration</a
      > of 2023 onward.
    </p>

    <h3 id="naic">National AI Centre (NAIC)</h3>
    <p>
      The NAIC is the industry-facing centre: the voluntary-guidance counterpart to
      the DTA&rsquo;s mandatory rules for agencies. It was <a
        href="https://www.minister.industry.gov.au/ministers/price/media-releases/launch-national-artificial-intelligence-centre-back-australias-ai-future"
        >launched on 14 December 2021</a
      > inside CSIRO&rsquo;s Data61 under the Morrison government&rsquo;s AI Action
      Plan, with Stela Solar as inaugural director. It convened the <a
        href="https://www.csiro.au/en/news/all/news/2023/march/australia-announces-world-first-responsible-ai-network-to-uplift-industry"
        >Responsible AI Network</a
      > in 2023 before a 2024&ndash;25 Budget decision <a
        href="https://www.innovationaus.com/national-ai-centre-stripped-from-csiro-in-40m-policy-shift/"
        >moved it out of CSIRO and into DISR</a
      >. Its <a href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/voluntary-ai-safety-standard"
        >Voluntary AI Safety Standard</a
      > of September 2024 set out ten voluntary guardrails, since folded into the
      leaner <a
        href="https://www.ai.gov.au/staying-safe-and-responsible/essential-ai-practices/guidance-ai-adoption-implementation-guidance"
        >Guidance for AI Adoption</a
      > of October 2025. <a href="https://www.ai.gov.au/about/about-national-ai-centre"
        >Led by Lee Hickin</a
      > since March 2025, it is a key delivery body for the National AI Plan and
      runs the government&rsquo;s public AI portal, ai.gov.au.
    </p>

    <h3 id="aisi">Australian AI Safety Institute</h3>
    <p>
      The institute is the newest of the DISR bodies, <a
        href="https://www.industry.gov.au/news/australia-establish-new-institute-strengthen-ai-safety"
        >announced on 25 November 2025</a
      > with $29.9 million and operational from early 2026. It tests advanced AI
      systems, assesses their risks and harms, and maps regulatory gaps. That work
      is advisory; the institute has <a
        href="https://www.minister.industry.gov.au/ministers/timayres/media-releases/establishment-australian-ai-safety-institute"
        >no enforcement powers</a
      >. It joined the international network of AI safety institutes.
    </p>

    <h3 id="office-of-ai">Office of AI (Prime Minister and Cabinet)</h3>
    <p>
      The Office of AI is the newcomer. In a speech on 15 July 2026, Prime Minister
      Anthony Albanese <a
        href="https://www.abc.net.au/news/2026-07-14/albanese-maps-out-ai-future-introducing-national-framework/106915094"
        >announced the office</a
      > within his own department and declared the end of the government&rsquo;s
      &ldquo;issue-by-issue&rdquo; approach. Australia, he said, would be the first
      country to bring AI policy into &ldquo;a single, national framework&rdquo;.
      The office is to <a
        href="https://theconversation.com/view-from-the-hill-albanese-takes-oversight-of-governments-response-to-ai-under-his-own-wing-287494"
        >coordinate the design of Australian standards</a
      > for the technology and to pull together the threads running through other
      ministers&rsquo; portfolios: data-centre approvals with the states, copyright,
      AI at work and in schools, defence and national security. It will work with
      Minister Ayres and Assistant Minister Charlton. At the time of writing, no
      head, budget or staffing had been announced, and how the office relates to
      AIDE, the DTA or the NAIC had not been spelled out. The opposition <a
        href="https://www.abc.net.au/news/2026-07-14/albanese-maps-out-ai-future-introducing-national-framework/106915094"
        >dismissed it</a
      > as &ldquo;an office in an office &hellip; inside his own office&rdquo;.
    </p>

    <h3 id="around">Around them</h3>
    <p>
      A ring of other bodies has a hand in the policy without owning it. The <a
        href="https://www.finance.gov.au/government/public-data/data-and-digital-ministers-meeting/national-framework-assurance-artificial-intelligence-government"
        >Data and Digital Ministers Meeting</a
      >, the Commonwealth&ndash;state forum, agreed a national framework for
      assuring AI in government in June 2024. Parliament has weighed in repeatedly.
      The <a
        href="https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Adopting_Artificial_Intelligence_AI/AdoptingAI/Report"
        >Senate Select Committee on Adopting AI</a
      > recommended a dedicated AI Act in November 2024; the government&rsquo;s <a
        href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/australian-government-response-senate-select-committee-adopting-artificial-intelligence-ai-report"
        >response</a
      > arrived in April 2026, after the National AI Plan had gone the other way.
      The audit committee&rsquo;s <a
        href="https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Joint/Public_Accounts_and_Audit/PublicsectoruseofAI/Report"
        ><em>Proceed with Caution</em></a
      > report of March 2025 called for standing parliamentary oversight of AI, and
      a <a
        href="https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Environment_and_Communications/AIdatacentres48P"
        >Senate inquiry into AI and data centres</a
      > opened in May 2026. The regulators publish AI guidance within their existing
      remits rather than holding policy carriage: the <a
        href="https://www.oaic.gov.au/privacy/privacy-guidance-for-organisations-and-government-agencies/guidance-on-privacy-and-the-use-of-commercially-available-ai-products"
        >privacy regulator</a
      > on AI products (2024), <a
        href="https://www.esafety.gov.au/newsroom/media-releases/new-industry-codes-seek-to-take-on-ai-chatbots-that-encourage-suicide-and-engage-in-sexually-explicit-conversations-with-aussie-kids"
        >eSafety</a
      > through industry codes covering generative AI and companion chatbots (2025),
      the <a
        href="https://www.asd.gov.au/news/2024-01-24-new-guidance-engaging-artificial-intelligence"
        >signals directorate</a
      > on secure use of AI (2024), and the <a
        href="https://www.anao.gov.au/work/performance-audit/governance-of-artificial-intelligence-the-australian-taxation-office"
        >national audit office</a
      > through agency-by-agency AI governance audits. On copyright, the issue that
      shadows every data-centre deal, the Attorney-General&rsquo;s Department
      convenes the <a
        href="https://www.ag.gov.au/rights-and-protections/copyright/copyright-and-artificial-intelligence-reference-group-cairg"
        >Copyright and Artificial Intelligence Reference Group</a
      >.
    </p>

    <h2 id="timeline">How it grew</h2>
    <p>
      A hand-picked chronology of the moments that built the current arrangement.
      Dates are the official publication or announcement dates in the linked
      sources.
    </p>
    <ul class="policy-tl">
      <li>
        <time datetime="2019-11-07">7 Nov 2019</time>
        <div>
          Australia&rsquo;s <a
            href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/australias-ai-ethics-principles"
            >AI Ethics Principles</a
          > published &mdash; eight voluntary principles, developed with CSIRO&rsquo;s
          Data61, that still underpin the frameworks that followed.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2021-06-18">18 Jun 2021</time>
        <div>
          The Morrison government&rsquo;s <a
            href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/australias-artificial-intelligence-action-plan"
            >AI Action Plan</a
          > commits $124.1&nbsp;million under the Digital Economy Strategy, including
          funding for a national AI centre.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2021-12-14">14 Dec 2021</time>
        <div>
          The <a
            href="https://www.minister.industry.gov.au/ministers/price/media-releases/launch-national-artificial-intelligence-centre-back-australias-ai-future"
            >National AI Centre launches</a
          > inside CSIRO&rsquo;s Data61, with Stela Solar as inaugural director.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2023-03-16">16 Mar 2023</time>
        <div>
          NAIC convenes the <a
            href="https://www.csiro.au/en/news/all/news/2023/march/australia-announces-world-first-responsible-ai-network-to-uplift-industry"
            >Responsible AI Network</a
          > for industry.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2023-06-01">1 Jun 2023</time>
        <div>
          DISR opens the <a href="https://consult.industry.gov.au/supporting-responsible-ai"
            >safe and responsible AI consultation</a
          >; it draws more than 500 submissions.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2023-07-06">6 Jul 2023</time>
        <div>
          The DTA and DISR publish <a
            href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/interim-guidance-generative-ai-government-agencies"
            >interim guidance</a
          > on public servants&rsquo; use of generative AI.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2023-09-19">19 Sep 2023</time>
        <div>
          Ministers Husic and Gallagher announce the <a
            href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/ai-government-taskforce-examining-use-and-governance-ai-aps"
            >AI in Government Taskforce</a
          >, jointly led by the DTA and DISR.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2023-11-02">2 Nov 2023</time>
        <div>
          Australia signs the <a
            href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/bletchley-declaration-countries-attending-ai-safety-summit-1-2-november-2023"
            >Bletchley Declaration</a
          > at the first global AI Safety Summit.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2023-12-05">5 Dec 2023</time>
        <div>
          The Attorney-General&rsquo;s Department convenes the <a
            href="https://www.ag.gov.au/rights-and-protections/copyright/copyright-and-artificial-intelligence-reference-group-cairg"
            >Copyright and AI Reference Group</a
          >.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2024-01-17">17 Jan 2024</time>
        <div>
          The government&rsquo;s <a
            href="https://www.industry.gov.au/news/australian-governments-interim-response-safe-and-responsible-ai-consultation"
            >interim response</a
          > to the consultation promises a risk-based approach and guardrails for
          high-risk AI.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2024-02-14">14 Feb 2024</time>
        <div>
          An <a
            href="https://www.minister.industry.gov.au/ministers/husic/media-releases/new-artificial-intelligence-expert-group"
            >AI Expert Group</a
          > chaired by Aur&eacute;lie Jacquet is appointed to steer the design of
          mandatory guardrails.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2024-03-26">26 Mar 2024</time>
        <div>
          The Senate establishes the <a
            href="https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Adopting_Artificial_Intelligence_AI/AdoptingAI/Report"
            >Select Committee on Adopting AI</a
          >.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2024-06-21">21 Jun 2024</time>
        <div>
          Commonwealth, state and territory ministers agree the <a
            href="https://www.finance.gov.au/government/public-data/data-and-digital-ministers-meeting/national-framework-assurance-artificial-intelligence-government"
            >national framework for the assurance of AI in government</a
          >.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2024-06-30">30 Jun 2024</time>
        <div>
          The AI in Government Taskforce winds up; the DTA <a
            href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/responsible-choices-new-policy-using-ai-australian-government"
            >carries its work forward</a
          >. The six-month <a href="https://www.digital.gov.au/initiatives/copilot-trial"
            >Microsoft 365 Copilot trial</a
          > across the APS also concludes.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2024-07-05">5 Jul 2024</time>
        <div>
          The National AI Centre&rsquo;s <a
            href="https://www.innovationaus.com/national-ai-centre-stripped-from-csiro-in-40m-policy-shift/"
            >move from CSIRO into DISR</a
          > is confirmed, following a May Budget decision.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2024-08-15">15 Aug 2024</time>
        <div>
          Minister Gallagher announces the <a
            href="https://ministers.finance.gov.au/financeminister/media-release/2024/08/15/new-policy-use-ai-government"
            ><em>Policy for the responsible use of AI in government</em></a
          >, effective 1 September: the policy that mandates accountable officials
          and AI transparency statements.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2024-09-05">5 Sep 2024</time>
        <div>
          DISR releases the <a
            href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/voluntary-ai-safety-standard"
            >Voluntary AI Safety Standard</a
          > alongside a <a href="https://consult.industry.gov.au/ai-mandatory-guardrails"
            >proposals paper for mandatory guardrails</a
          > on high-risk AI.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2024-11-26">26 Nov 2024</time>
        <div>
          The Senate select committee&rsquo;s <a
            href="https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Adopting_Artificial_Intelligence_AI/AdoptingAI/Report"
            >final report</a
          > recommends a dedicated AI Act.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2024-12-16">16 Dec 2024</time>
        <div>
          Minister Husic announces work on a <a
            href="https://www.minister.industry.gov.au/ministers/husic/media-releases/australian-first-ai-plan-boost-capability"
            >National AI Capability Plan</a
          >, to be developed over 2025.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2025-02-28">28 Feb 2025</time>
        <div>
          The <a
            href="https://www.digital.gov.au/ai/ai-in-government-policy/standard-ai-transparency-statements"
            >deadline for AI transparency statements</a
          > takes effect. These are the documents this site <a href={withBase("/agencies")}
            >tracks agency by agency</a
          >.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2025-03-04">4 Mar 2025</time>
        <div>
          Parliament&rsquo;s audit committee tables <a
            href="https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Joint/Public_Accounts_and_Audit/PublicsectoruseofAI/Report"
            ><em>Proceed with Caution</em></a
          >, recommending a standing joint committee on AI.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2025-05-13">13 May 2025</time>
        <div>
          The post-election reshuffle drops Ed Husic; <a
            href="https://www.minister.industry.gov.au/ministers/timayres">Tim Ayres</a
          > takes industry and innovation, with <a
            href="https://www.minister.industry.gov.au/charlton">Andrew Charlton</a
          > as Assistant Minister for Science, Technology and the Digital Economy.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2025-07-31">31 Jul 2025</time>
        <div>
          Finance <a
            href="https://ministers.finance.gov.au/financeminister/media-release/2025/07/31/govai-launch-marks-major-milestone-ai-aps"
            >opens GovAI to the whole APS</a
          >; the DTA publishes its <a
            href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/new-ai-technical-standard-support-responsible-government-adoption"
            >AI technical standard</a
          > the same day.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2025-10-21">21 Oct 2025</time>
        <div>
          NAIC&rsquo;s <a
            href="https://www.ai.gov.au/staying-safe-and-responsible/essential-ai-practices/guidance-ai-adoption-implementation-guidance"
            >Guidance for AI Adoption</a
          > replaces the voluntary standard&rsquo;s ten guardrails with six
          practices.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2025-11-12">12 Nov 2025</time>
        <div>
          Senator Gallagher <a
            href="https://ministers.finance.gov.au/financeminister/speech/2025/11/12/launch-ai-plan-australian-public-service"
            >launches the APS AI Plan</a
          >: AIDE, GovAI Chat, chief AI officers, an AI review committee and
          mandatory training. Continuous tracking on this site <a
            href={withBase("/about")}>opened the day before</a
          >.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2025-11-25">25 Nov 2025</time>
        <div>
          An <a
            href="https://www.industry.gov.au/news/australia-establish-new-institute-strengthen-ai-safety"
            >Australian AI Safety Institute</a
          > is announced within DISR, with $29.9&nbsp;million.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2025-12-02">2 Dec 2025</time>
        <div>
          The <a
            href="https://www.industry.gov.au/news/australia-launches-national-ai-plan-capture-opportunities-share-benefits-and-keep-australians-safe"
            >National AI Plan</a
          > is published: existing law over a dedicated AI Act, and the
          mandatory-guardrails proposal does not proceed.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2025-12-15">15 Dec 2025</time>
        <div>
          <a href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/ai-policy-update-strengthening-responsible-use-across-government"
            >Version 2.0 of the AI-in-government policy</a
          > takes effect, adding AI impact assessments, procurement guidance and
          mandatory training.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2026-03-31">31 Mar 2026</time>
        <div>
          The DTA opens a <a
            href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/new-central-register-ai-transparency-statements-commonwealth-entities"
            >central register of AI transparency statements</a
          >, reporting all 94 obliged agencies compliant and 20 publishing
          voluntarily.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2026-04-01">1 Apr 2026</time>
        <div>
          The government&rsquo;s <a
            href="https://www.industry.gov.au/publications/australian-government-response-senate-select-committee-adopting-artificial-intelligence-ai-report"
            >response to the Senate select committee</a
          > is tabled.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2026-04-28">28 Apr 2026</time>
        <div>
          <a href="https://www.finance.gov.au/about-us/news/2026/govai-chat-alpha-trial-now-open-sign-now"
            >GovAI Chat&rsquo;s alpha trial</a
          > opens to the APS.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2026-05-13">13 May 2026</time>
        <div>
          The Senate refers an <a
            href="https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Environment_and_Communications/AIdatacentres48P"
            >inquiry into AI and data centres</a
          >, reporting November 2026.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2026-07-01">1 Jul 2026</time>
        <div>
          The chief AI officer deadline passes with <a
            href="https://ia.acs.org.au/article/2026/govt-agencies-that-missed-the-chief-ai-officer-deadline.html"
            >104 of 106 agencies appointing one</a
          >.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <time datetime="2026-07-15">15 Jul 2026</time>
        <div>
          Prime Minister Albanese <a
            href="https://www.abc.net.au/news/2026-07-14/albanese-maps-out-ai-future-introducing-national-framework/106915094"
            >announces the Office of AI</a
          > within his own department, to bring the threads into &ldquo;a single,
          national framework&rdquo;.
        </div>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="corrections">Corrections</h2>
    <p>
      Machinery of government moves faster than hand-curated pages. If something
      here is out of date or wrong, please <a
        href="https://github.com/ANUcybernetics/aps-ai-tracker/issues"
        >open an issue</a
      >.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>

